ns. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":71,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.go